They provided the two dipping sauces in tiny containers. Our friends LOVED the gift and they were delicious! Great service. Yummy. Local.

Probably because it had not cooked long enough to thicken..The seasoning had  not formulated either...If you are going to open at 11 THEN STUFF NEEDS TO BE READY AT 11..

i was so full. i had a cousin come into town and asked me to take him back here. it has a great feel to it. makes me feel like i am back in tucson.

This family is so wonderfully kind and you get exactly what you came for ; American fast food of the Indian variety. It’s inexpensive and they have SO DAMN MANY vegetarian and vegan options unlike many places to eat in Chicago. This is a good place for Indian food ‘beginners’ to start their flavor journeys before graduating to higher end more fragrant dishes/restaurants. I wouldn’t say it’s authentic from a traditional sense, and my best example of this would be a fancy Mexican restaurant vs a mom and pop quick taco pick up. Both are yummy one is more elaborate and caters to the purist, while the other fills you up in a tasty way. I lived in London (Brixton) for a bit and ate Indian food like Er’day lol ...it’s great to know I support an actual family when I patron there and they always make me feel welcome.
THEY HAVE THE BEST SOMASAS!!! AAAAAND THEIR PEICES ARE AMAZING!!🙏🏿🙏🏿

I had to review this place as it is probably my new favorite Indian restaurant in all of chicago (and I've tried many) The menu caught my eye when I was walking down the street and I had to try - I got the butter chicken combo meal with dal curry (very cheap at only $12.49) and was blown away by how good every single item was. Another important reason I rate this restaurant so highly is because of how the menu is formatted - basically all the hits are on there and nothing unnecessary. Quite a concise menu for an Indian restaurant (not to mention the southern dishes) which I think would make it friendly for someone not familiar with these cuisines. Everything is translated or clarified for americans and it is more of an American style single person portions - most indian restaurants are oriented towards family-style groups and portions/price reflect this. I also had the peach cobbler and gulab jaman which were both great! My only complaint is that I did not know about this place sooner!
Got there about three, it wasn't crowded. There was quick, helpful, and friendly service.

We moved to Hyde Park in the winter of 2020, and I just was able to sample the food here very recently.  I can't say I am sorry I waited so long.  The first time I attempted the restaurant I parked on 53rd and walked up at 8:10 (after a 12 hour shift on the front lines!). The guy, while polite, was like no "these hours are wrong, we're closed". I was craving good Indian which this is the only South Asian food available for miles, so while disappointed the owner didn't seem interested in my business I wanted so much to try again and enjoy the food (and turn that negative encounter into a positive one)  Unfortunately, nah. I got the veggie platter with aloo gobi and dal.  They tasted way too sweet!  The rice had ok flavor. Paratha solid. Samosa was fine.  Will not go out of my way to return.  Sunny store front is nice.

There are not many Indian restaurants on the south side of Chicago, but this one is in Hyde Park.  I suspect that when it opened the owner thought that they would compete against "Popeye's Chicken", hence then name "Rajun Cajun", but found that they sold just as much, if not more, Indian dishes.  I would guess that the majority of there business is take out.  The restaurant is small with few tables.  Eating there is fine, I'm sure, for the many U of C student in the neighborhood, but most post college people will want to just take out.  The Indian menu is limited to about five item and about eight sides.  Of course they have Tandoori Chicken and an optional vegetarian selection.  The food is quite decent although it will not compete with the larger Indian restaurants you fine on Chicago's far north side.

Fantastic. One of our favorite Hyde park spots for something quick.

Curry isn't even a traditional Indian dish, it was made up for the British!  It might be good food, but please know there is nothing from Louisiana in this place.  Offense taken.

This place is the best. I can't function properly if I haven't had it in a while. It looks kind of small and sketchy on the outside, but the food is amazing and the family that runs it is super nice. They have such a great selection of curries (buttered chicken, matar paneer, saag paneer, etc.) and quite a few vegetarian options, which includes their awesome samosas. They also give you a ton of food for how much you end up spending. The dinner combos are nice if you're dining there or eating alone, but if you have a group of people eating together I strongly recommend ordering mediums to larges of a few items a la carte and sharing them. You'll probably still have leftovers anyway. My other rule of thumb is to always get one more samosa than you think you'll actually want to eat. This has never backfired on me.

I love this place.  I make a point to stop in every time I am back in Chicago.  I swear to god they make the best samosas in the world here.  It is small, the selection is not tremendous, but the food they do have is mouth watering.  And Indian food and Cajun food mix very well.  Samosas, chana masala, and collard greens.  MMMmmmmmmmmm
Good Indian food in Hyde Park. A hidden gem if a restaurant. They serve ample portions. This place serves a variety of Indian, vegetarian & Soul Food dishes. Consistently fast service!

I got hooked on Rajun Cajun from the individual microwaveable plates they have in the student-run cafes at the University of Chicago. The vegetarian Indian food is just spicy enough and super flavorful. Their mix of southern food (which i haven't tried) and Indian food makes me smile every time I walk in. Portions are plentiful!

Rajun Cajun is a bit of a dive with the decor on the inside. They serve decent quality Indian fast food (one of the only places to do so in Hyde Park), although the prices have increased in the past few months. The butter chicken, peas and cheese, samosas, and mango lasse are good. Rumor has it that they thread eyebrows in the back kitchen, so be alarmed of cleanliness.
The menu is small but the service is quick and the dishes are great

Doesn't look like much from the outside (or the inside) but the food is excellent and the service is as good as it could be. The owner and his wife went out of their way to talk to us about the area and places to see, you could really tell they love their community.  The indian food wasn't the best i've ever had but it was very good. I would visit hyde park again when i come to chicago specifically to go back here.

Rajun Cajun is one of my favorite locations in Hyde Park. The food is really delicious (and the portions are sizeable)! The delivery is very timely and I've never had a problem with an order mix-up. This place is very much a Hyde Park gem.
NEVER GOING BACK TO THIS PLACE, FOOD, SERVICE ALL SUCKED AND NOT CLEAN PLACE

From the outside, it looks like your normal everyday indian-food shack.  I hit this place up while traveling on the south side a few weeks ago and I was really happy with the food.  The atmosphere of the place is self is really lacking, but if you can see beyond that you'll be in for a treat when it comes to the food.
Great authentic Indian food. Lovely people, spartan inside, but the food is fantastic.
For 20+ years always great!
